    <title>Combined summary - CHECKSEQUENCEVERIFY - We need more usecases to motivate the change</title>
    <updated>2023-06-10T23:48:19.470547+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-October/011561.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Bitcoin developers are currently discussing proposals to implement new features in Bitcoin transactions using nSequence. The main focus of the discussion is on BIP68 and BIP112, which define the CHECKSEQUENCEVERIFY semantics. There are suggestions to use 16 bits for sequence numbers to remove ambiguity and lead to 14 bits for further soft forks within the semantics of BIP68. However, there are concerns about the need for a complex soft-fork that limits future upgrades.The email exchanges also include discussions on implementing relative CLTV using nSequence. Some developers express their concerns about the necessity of using nSequence for this purpose, while others believe it is necessary. Additionally, the use of RCLTV and OP_CSV is debated in the context of enforcing a delay between publishing a commitment transaction and spending the output in lightning commitment transactions.Several proposals were suggested for using nSequence, including discouraging miners from reorging chains and implementing proof-of-stake blocksize voting. Mark Friedenbach proposed keeping the highest possible precision with the expectation of decreasing granularity in the future if required. However, there were also suggestions for compromise solutions and updates to the BIP text.Overall, the email thread shows ongoing discussions and debates among the Bitcoin community regarding the best approaches for implementing new features and upgrading the system. It is important to justify any new behavior carefully as it limits options in the future. The Bitcoin community needs to come up with more justification for the fairly complex soft-fork that limits future upgrades before deploying it.</summary>
